Actually, the domino effect is a hoax: It seems that the weight of the
previous falling brick starts the next, but it is mostly the force from
pushing the first piece that really is transferred. If you push the first one
carefully forward until the gravity takes over, that little force from
just falling will not be strong enough to continue, so somewhere along
the brick road the falling will fade out and stop. That is also proven in this clip. Every clip I have
seen elsewhere of domino tricks show the starter giving the first brick a heavily
and hard push. Something to think and ask questions about when you try
to explain the twin tower collaps as a domino effect: The falling tower
accelerates on the way down, but the top was not thrown against the next floor below, and every floor below is stronger and stronger than the previous as it was constructed to hold more weight. Explain THAT Mythbusters :-)
Now get Lily Hevesh to try it.

Having not clearly seen the inside of the larger dominoes I wonder if weight distribution was the reason the last one didn't go over without help. If the center of mass was significantly below the vertical midpoint or closer to the impact side than car side that would make it more difficult to tip over. Conversely a high center of mass or one closer to the car would be easier to tip over.
